🧠 PRD: Guardian Angel Microservice
1. Product Overview
Name: Guardian Angel Microservice
Type: Internal AI Ops Microservice
One-liner:
An AI-first incident responder that detects, diagnoses, and resolves low-impact microservice issues before escalating to developers.
2. Problem Statement
Modern microservice systems suffer from:
Alert fatigue — too many low-severity issues reach engineers
Slow response time — every issue enters human workflow
Repetitive fixes — same incidents solved manually again and again
Result:
wasted engineering time
delayed resolution
inefficient operations
3. Goal (Hackathon Scope)
Build a system that:
detects a low-impact incident
performs AI-based diagnosis
executes a pre-approved recovery action
verifies recovery
escalates only if needed
4. Non-Goals (Important)
To keep scope tight:
❌ No full infra automation
❌ No high-risk actions (DB writes, config changes)
❌ No multi-service orchestration
❌ No production-grade security/compliance
5. Target User
Backend engineers
DevOps engineers
Platform teams
6. Core Use Case (MVP)
🎯 Scenario: Stuck Worker / Failing Service
Service health degrades (e.g. job queue stuck)
Guardian detects anomaly
AI summarizes logs + metrics
Maps to known issue pattern
Executes safe action:
restart worker OR
retry job OR
rollback deploy
Verifies recovery
If fail → escalate with summary
7. Key Features
7.1 Incident Detection
Inputs:
health endpoint (/health)
error rate
queue depth (optional)
Output:
incident event
7.2 AI Diagnosis Engine
Uses:
logs
metrics
recent deployments
Output:
root cause hypothesis
confidence score
suggested action
7.3 Service Registry (Critical)
Each service defines:
{
  "service": "email-worker",
  "safe_actions": [
    "restart_worker",
    "retry_jobs"
  ],
  "incident_patterns": [
    "queue_stuck",
    "worker_crash"
  ]
}
7.4 Remediation Engine
Executes only:
pre-approved actions
Examples:
restart pod
retry job
rollback deployment (optional stretch)
7.5 Verification Engine
Checks:
health restored
error rate reduced
queue draining
7.6 Escalation System
If unresolved:
send alert (Slack / console)
include:
summary
attempted fixes
suspected cause
8. System Architecture
Components:
1. Event Listener
listens to alerts / simulated triggers
2. Agent Orchestrator
controls flow: detect → diagnose → act
3. Diagnosis Agent
LLM-based reasoning over logs
4. Action Engine
executes safe actions
5. Service Registry
defines allowed actions per service
6. Verification Module
checks if issue resolved
7. Notification Module
escalates to human
9. Data Flow
Alert Triggered
     ↓
Incident Created
     ↓
Diagnosis Agent (LLM)
     ↓
Action Decision (Policy Check)
     ↓
Remediation Action
     ↓
Verification
     ↓
[Resolved] OR [Escalate]
10. Example Demo Flow (Very Important)
Demo Story:
Simulate:
worker stops processing jobs
System detects:
queue depth rising
AI outputs:
“Worker likely stuck due to missing heartbeat. Recommended action: restart_worker (confidence: 0.87)”
System executes:
restart worker
UI shows:
queue draining
health restored
Status:
✅ Auto-resolved
11. Success Metrics (Hackathon Level)
% of incidents auto-resolved
time to resolution (vs manual)
reduction in developer escalation
12. Tech Stack (Suggested)
Keep it simple:
Backend: Node.js / Python (FastAPI)
LLM: OpenAI / Claude / local model
Infra Simulation: Docker / simple services
Execution Layer: scripts or mocked actions
UI (optional): React dashboard
13. MVP Scope (Strict)
Must have:
1 microservice (simulated)
1 failure scenario
2–3 safe actions
basic AI diagnosis
simple verification
Nice to have:
rollback deploy
multiple services
confidence scoring UI
14. Risks
AI hallucination → solved via action allowlist
over-automation → solved via low-risk scope
unclear diagnosis → fallback to escalation
15. Future Vision (Don’t build now, just mention)
multi-service dependency healing
predictive failure detection
infra-level automation (K8s, cloud)
blockchain node recovery
sustainability asset healing
🧾 Final Positioning (use this in pitch)
“Guardian Angel is an AI-powered microservice that acts as the first responder for software incidents — automatically diagnosing and resolving low-impact issues before engineers are involved.”
